1) No, if @Autowired is already put on the constructor or setter, it is not necessary to also put it on the field. 

2) Sure! Here's a concise example:

```java
public interface Animal {
    void makeSound();
}

@Component
public class Cat implements Animal {
    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Meow!");
    }
}

@Component
public class Dog implements Animal {
    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Woof!");
    }
}

@Component
public class AnimalService {
    private final Animal animal;

    @Autowired
    public AnimalService(Animal animal) {
        this.animal = animal;
    }

    public void makeAnimalSound() {
        animal.makeSound();
    }
}
```

In this example, we have an interface `Animal` and two concrete classes `Cat` and `Dog` that implement the `Animal` interface. The `AnimalService` class has a dependency on the `Animal` interface. By annotating the constructor parameter in `AnimalService` with `@Autowired`, Spring will automatically inject an instance of `Cat` or `Dog` (whichever is available) into the constructor based on configuration and component scanning. We can then use the `animal` field to call the `makeSound()` method of the injected `Animal` instance.

Note: Proper configuration and component scanning setup in the Spring application context would be required for this example to work.

